#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:217
msgid "Feedback Loop"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:219
msgid ""
"One of the basic concepts of control theory is using feedback loops "
"either for neutralizing the disturbances from the surroundings or a "
"desire for a smoother output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:223
msgid ""
"In :numref:`omnotebook-feedback`, control of a simple car model is "
"illustrated where the car velocity on a road is controlled, first with an"
" open loop control, and then compared to a closed loop system with a "
"feedback loop. The car has a mass m, velocity y, and aerodynamic "
"coefficient α. The θ is the road slope, which in this case can be "
"regarded as noise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:232
msgid "Feedback loop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:234
msgid "Lets look at the Modelica model for the open loop controlled car:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:236
msgid "m \\dot y = u - \\alpha y - m g * sin(\\theta)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:257
msgid ""
"By applying a road slope angle different from zero the car velocity is "
"influenced which can be regarded as noise in this model. The output "
"signal in :numref:`omnotebook-open-loop` is stable but an overshoot can "
"be observed compared to the reference signal. Naturally the overshoot is "
"not desired and the student will in the next exercise learn how to get "
"rid of this undesired behavior of the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../<OMC gnuplot>:1
msgid "Open loop control example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:277
msgid "The closed car model with a proportional regulator is shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:279
msgid "u = K*(r-y)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:302
msgid ""
"By using the information about the current level of the output signal and"
" re-tune the regulator the output quantity can be controlled towards the "
"reference signal smoothly and without an overshoot, as shown in :numref"
":`omnotebook-closed-loop`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:307
msgid ""
"In the above simple example the flat modeling approach was adopted since "
"it was the fastest one to quickly obtain a working model. However, one "
"could use the object oriented approach and encapsulate the car and "
"regulator models in separate classes with the Modelica connector "
"mechanism in between."
msgstr ""

#: ../../<OMC gnuplot>:1
msgid "Closed loop control example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:327
msgid "Mathematical Modeling with Characteristic Equations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:329
msgid ""
"In most systems the relation between the inputs and outputs can be "
"described by a linear differential equation. Tearing apart the solution "
"of the differential equation into homogenous and particular parts is an "
"important technique taught to the students in engineering courses, also "
"illustrated in :numref:`omnotebook-mathematical-modeling-with-"
"characteristic-equation`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:335
msgid ""
"{{\\partial ^{n}y}\\over{\\partial t^n}} + a_1 {{\\partial "
"^{n-1}y}\\over{\\partial t^{n-1}}} + \\ldots + a_n y = b_0 {{\\partial "
"^{m}u} \\over {\\partial t^m}} + \\ldots + b_{m-1} {{\\partial "
"u}\\over{\\partial t}} + b_m u"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:341
msgid "Now let us examine a second order system:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:343
msgid "\\ddot y + a_1 \\dot y + a_2 y = 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:359
msgid ""
"Choosing different values for a\\ :sub:`1` and a\\ :sub:`2` leads to "
"different behavior as shown in :numref:`omnotebook-drcontrol-negroots` "
"and :numref:`omnotebook-drcontrol-imgposroots`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:365
msgid "Mathematical modeling with characteristic equation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:367
msgid ""
"In the first example the values of a\\ :sub:`1` and a\\ :sub:`2` are "
"chosen in such way that the characteristic equation has negative real "
"roots and thereby a stable output response, see :numref:`omnotebook-"
"drcontrol-negroots`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../<OMC gnuplot>:1
msgid "Characteristic equation with real negative roots."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/omnotebook.rst:381
msgid ""
"The importance of the sign of the roots in the characteristic equation is"
" illustrated in :numref:`omnotebook-drcontrol-negroots` and :numref"
":`omnotebook-drcontrol-imgposroots`, e.g., a stable system with negative "
"real roots and an unstable system with positive imaginary roots resulting"
" in oscillations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../<OMC gnuplot>:1
msgid "Characteristic equation with imaginary roots with positive real part."
msgstr ""

